{
  "text": "In order to apply the model, we use the crystallite size as measured by X-ray line broadening in q-2q scans (all the q-2q scans of the as-deposited and annealed YSZ \ue103lms are provided in the ESI S-4 \u2020). In doing so, the implicit assumption being made, see ESI S-5, \u2020 is that grain size and growth is equiaxed. The starting stress (s o ) value used in these calculations is the sum of the growth stress (s g ) measured and thermal mismatch stress generated during the heating from growth temperature (700 C) to the annealing temperature (1000 C). In the present case the thermal mismatch stress is \u00c00.5 GPa (see ESI S-3 \u2020). Fig. 11 shows the change in \ue103lm energy vs. \ue103nal grain size of (111) YSZ \ue103lms with d 0 < d cr . It can be observed that there is an energy minimum for each \ue103lm. Final grain sizes of these \ue103lms a\ue09der annealing matches with the corresponding energy minimum in top of Fig. 11 . There is a close match between the experimental values (Fig. 11 top) and the calculated value the model (Fig. 11 bottom) . It can also be noticed that higher the initial compressive stress, larger the \ue103nal grain size. Fig. 12 shows plot of change in \ue103lm energy vs. \ue103nal grain size for (100) YSZ \ue103lms with d 0 > d cr . It can be noticed that there is no energy minimum as expected from the energy balance model. However, experimental results in the corresponding top \ue103gure shows grain growth saturation at some particular grain size. Note that the x-axis is up to 60 nm to make grain sizes clear, but no energy minimum was found even when x-axis was extended to >150 nm. This contradicts the model which predicts that if d 0 > d cr , grain should grow continuously and grain growth should not get saturated. To con\ue103rm whether the grain growth is actually limited by kinetics and not by thermodynamics, two of these \ue103lms with d 0 > d cr were annealed at a higher temperature (1200 C) for another hour. If there is no grain growth even at this higher temperature, then it can be concluded that the grain growth saturates due to limitation in diffusion of grain boundaries. It was observed that there was hardly any increase in grain size (see Fig. 13 ). Thus, the obvious reason for the lack of agreement with thermodynamic predictions seems to be due to the kinetics factors. It is to be noticed that the slope of the energy-grain size plot (J m \u00c01 or vm vx ) can be looked upon as a measure of kinetic driving force for grain growth. This slope for a \ue103lm with d 0 < d cr is higher ($one order of magnitude) than for a \ue103lm with d 0 > d cr (see Fig. 11 and 12 ). Therefore, kinetic driving force for atomic diffusion aiding grain growth is smaller for the latter case. Hence, grain growth was found to be restricted by kinetics, though thermodynamically there was no restriction for those \ue103lms with d 0 > d cr . While a detailed modelling of grain growth is out of the scope of this paper, it is very well known that the rate of grain growth scales inversely with the grain size. [CITATION_1] This is another reason which supports the experimental observation that there is kinetic limitation for grain growth in (100) YSZ \ue103lms with d 0 > d cr . Thus, while grain growth in a \ue103lm with large initial grain size (also d 0 > d cr ) might not be restrained by a thermodynamic minimum, it appears that it will be limited by kinetic factors.",
  "citation_candidates": [
